00:01:33.020 --> 00:01:33.200
ERIC BARKER: Yeah.

00:01:33.200 --> 00:01:34.400
This was really interesting.

00:01:34.400 --> 00:01:36.860
This was work done by Gautam
Mukunda at Harvard Business

00:01:36.860 --> 00:01:39.830
School.

00:01:39.830 --> 00:01:42.500
I connected strongly with
it because I'd been writing

00:01:42.500 --> 00:01:45.080
about research on leadership.

00:01:45.080 --> 00:01:47.030
And I noticed this
total discrepancy

00:01:47.030 --> 00:01:49.520
where half the
research was saying

00:01:49.520 --> 00:01:51.542
that leaders are essential.

00:01:51.542 --> 00:01:52.250
They're critical.

00:01:52.250 --> 00:01:53.440
They pull people together.

00:01:53.440 --> 00:01:56.687
They give people a mission and a
meaning and drive them forward.

00:01:56.687 --> 00:01:58.520
And the other half was
saying that if you've

00:01:58.520 --> 00:02:01.550
got a bunch of real A players,
they'll self-organize.

00:02:01.550 --> 00:02:04.282
You don't need some
figureheads taking the credit.

00:02:04.282 --> 00:02:05.740
And it was totally
a contradiction.

00:02:05.740 --> 00:02:06.800
And I was scratching my head.

00:02:06.800 --> 00:02:08.508
And then I came across
Gautam's research.

00:02:08.508 --> 00:02:10.449
And what he saw was
that there are actually

00:02:10.449 --> 00:02:12.190
two different kinds of leaders.

00:02:12.190 --> 00:02:14.380
There's filtered leaders
and unfiltered leaders.

00:02:14.380 --> 00:02:18.220
And basically, do leaders
make a difference?

00:02:18.220 --> 00:02:19.149
Do they not?

00:02:19.149 --> 00:02:21.190
Well, when you're talking
about filtered leaders,

00:02:21.190 --> 00:02:21.880
you are talking
about people who are

00:02:21.880 --> 00:02:24.760
going through a vetted system,
like in a typical hierarchical

00:02:24.760 --> 00:02:26.470
corporation.

00:02:26.470 --> 00:02:27.980
Those people are heavily vetted.

00:02:27.980 --> 00:02:31.454
So by the time anybody is in
the running for CEO of GE,

00:02:31.454 --> 00:02:33.370
they've been so thoroughly
vetted that they're

00:02:33.370 --> 00:02:34.411
almost indistinguishable.

00:02:34.411 --> 00:02:37.360
They would make the same
decisions as anybody else.

00:02:37.360 --> 00:02:39.620
So their decisions
don't have huge impact.

00:02:39.620 --> 00:02:41.657
Because if you pick one
person or the other,

00:02:41.657 --> 00:02:42.490
it's the same thing.

00:02:42.490 --> 00:02:43.948
Versus unfiltered
leaders-- so when

00:02:43.948 --> 00:02:46.180
you're talking about
entrepreneurs, when you're

00:02:46.180 --> 00:02:48.130
talking about if the
president steps down,

00:02:48.130 --> 00:02:50.664
the vice president, who
was not chosen, comes up.

00:02:50.664 --> 00:02:52.080
Those people are
less predictable.

00:02:52.080 --> 00:02:54.440
They weren't filtered the
same way through the system.

00:02:54.440 --> 00:02:57.310
So you can't expect them
to make the same decisions.

00:02:57.310 --> 00:02:59.410
So they aren't predictable.

00:02:59.410 --> 00:03:02.950
And they create big change.

00:03:02.950 --> 00:03:04.990
Change is a value-neutral word.

00:03:04.990 --> 00:03:07.240
Sometimes those changes are
bad, but sometimes you've

00:03:07.240 --> 00:03:10.390
got unfiltered leaders,
like Abraham Lincoln, who

00:03:10.390 --> 00:03:13.580
was a perfect storm that
resulted in him being elected.

00:03:13.580 --> 00:03:15.100
He ended slavery.

00:03:15.100 --> 00:03:17.770
So unfiltered leaders
create big changes.

00:03:17.770 --> 00:03:19.790
Filtered leaders not so much.

00:03:19.790 --> 00:03:21.370
But they each have their place.

00:03:21.370 --> 00:03:26.020
When you need a company or
organization to keep going,

00:03:26.020 --> 00:03:28.000
they're doing well,
prefer a filtered leader.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:31.211
And if you need changes, you
want an unfiltered leader.

00:03:31.211 --> 00:03:32.710
SPEAKER 1: And you
talk about ponds,

00:03:32.710 --> 00:03:34.715
like finding the right
pond for a leader.

00:03:34.715 --> 00:03:36.340
ERIC BARKER: What I
saw through looking

00:03:36.340 --> 00:03:40.810
at all the research on success
and talking to actually Gautam

00:03:40.810 --> 00:03:44.050
about this was that the
things that are really

00:03:44.050 --> 00:03:46.210
critical in terms of
success in any arena

00:03:46.210 --> 00:03:49.150
is first knowing yourself,
knowing your signature

00:03:49.150 --> 00:03:49.730
strengths.

00:03:49.730 --> 00:03:51.100
What are you good at?

00:03:51.100 --> 00:03:54.190
What are you uniquely good at?

00:03:54.190 --> 00:03:55.690
Because the more
time you spend--

00:03:55.690 --> 00:03:58.402
this is research you see from
the University of Pennsylvania

00:03:58.402 --> 00:04:00.860
in terms of when people exercise
their signature strengths,

00:04:00.860 --> 00:04:02.660
they are happier,
they're more successful.

00:04:02.660 --> 00:04:05.560
They feel more respected when
they do things they're good at.

00:04:05.560 --> 00:04:08.530
And then aligning yourself--
picking the right pond.

00:04:08.530 --> 00:04:10.780
In other words, what's
a place that respects

00:04:10.780 --> 00:04:12.420
and values what you do?

00:04:12.420 --> 00:04:15.250
Because you can be
great at something,

00:04:15.250 --> 00:04:17.440
but if you're not
in a place that

00:04:17.440 --> 00:04:19.600
really respects and
rewards that, you're going

00:04:19.600 --> 00:04:20.350
have a tough time.

00:04:20.350 --> 00:04:23.440
So it's aligning knowing thy
self, picking the right pond.

00:04:23.440 --> 00:04:25.180
When those two are
in alignment, you're

00:04:25.180 --> 00:04:29.150
in a really good position to be
successful in whatever you do.

00:04:29.150 --> 00:04:31.210
SPEAKER 1: That ties into
