00:04:31.210 --> 00:04:32.470
Can you go into that?

00:04:32.470 --> 00:04:33.220
ERIC BARKER: Yeah.

00:04:33.220 --> 00:04:35.011
That's something that's
really interesting.

00:04:35.011 --> 00:04:37.540
Because grit is kind of having
its time in the sun now,

00:04:37.540 --> 00:04:39.689
and everybody's talking
about being gritty.

00:04:39.689 --> 00:04:41.230
And the truth is,
we all quit things.

00:04:41.230 --> 00:04:42.188
We have to quit things.

00:04:42.188 --> 00:04:44.470
Otherwise, I'd still be
playing with action figures

00:04:44.470 --> 00:04:45.270
and playing t-ball.

00:04:45.270 --> 00:04:46.429
We all quit things.

00:04:46.429 --> 00:04:47.470
You need to move forward.

00:04:47.470 --> 00:04:49.450
So it's more of an issue
of what do you quit?

00:04:49.450 --> 00:04:51.010
When do you quit?

00:04:51.010 --> 00:04:54.310
And there was some really
interesting research

00:04:54.310 --> 00:04:56.500
by Gabriele Oettingen
at NYU, where

00:04:56.500 --> 00:05:00.040
she talked about this funny
little word called "WOOP."

00:05:00.040 --> 00:05:07.000
And it's an acronym for when the
issue-- you want to first wish,

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:09.580
then it's the issue of
what's the outcome you want,

00:05:09.580 --> 00:05:11.850
the obstacle, and then the plan.

00:05:11.850 --> 00:05:12.820
Those are four steps.

00:05:12.820 --> 00:05:14.440
Because we all like to dream.

00:05:14.440 --> 00:05:17.800
But the truth is research
shows when we dream we actually

00:05:17.800 --> 00:05:20.350
sap our energy, because our
brains aren't good at telling

00:05:20.350 --> 00:05:21.730
fiction from reality.

00:05:21.730 --> 00:05:23.650
That's why movies are exciting.

00:05:23.650 --> 00:05:26.770
So when we dream we
can actually sap energy

00:05:26.770 --> 00:05:29.230
if we don't go to the next
step, which is first is wish.

00:05:29.230 --> 00:05:32.110
Second is to really think,
what's the outcome you want?

00:05:32.110 --> 00:05:35.110
What is the crystal clear
thing you want to achieve?

00:05:35.110 --> 00:05:36.376
And then-- once you wish--

00:05:36.376 --> 00:05:38.500
outcome, then you have to
think about the obstacle.

00:05:38.500 --> 00:05:39.670
That's the tough part.

00:05:39.670 --> 00:05:40.930
What's in the way?

00:05:40.930 --> 00:05:43.600
What is stopping you from
getting what you want?

00:05:43.600 --> 00:05:45.100
And then the fourth
part is a plan.

00:05:45.100 --> 00:05:48.100
How are you going to
overcome that obstacle?

00:05:48.100 --> 00:05:51.046
When people walk
through that then

00:05:51.046 --> 00:05:52.420
you're really in
a good position.

00:05:52.420 --> 00:05:56.400
That's what's called in academia
implementation intentions.

00:05:56.400 --> 00:05:58.630
You're really in a good
position to move forward.

00:05:58.630 --> 00:06:01.540
But the secondary effect
is really fascinating.

00:06:01.540 --> 00:06:03.670
When people go through
this WOOP exercise,

00:06:03.670 --> 00:06:06.010
if they feel energized,
if they feel better

00:06:06.010 --> 00:06:09.430
about their goals, that
generally indicates,

00:06:09.430 --> 00:06:12.430
the research shows,
that they're realistic.

00:06:12.430 --> 00:06:14.110
That this is something
they could do.

00:06:14.110 --> 00:06:16.150
And if they feel
de-energized, the goal

00:06:16.150 --> 00:06:18.020
is probably unrealistic.

00:06:18.020 --> 00:06:20.530
So using that WOOP exercise
can really help people

00:06:20.530 --> 00:06:23.320
decide when to use
grit and when to quit.

00:06:23.320 --> 00:06:25.692
Because they'll look at
their dreams, their wishes,

00:06:25.692 --> 00:06:26.650
they walk through this.

00:06:26.650 --> 00:06:28.441
They can see if they
have an adequate plan,

00:06:28.441 --> 00:06:29.560
if that goal's reachable.

00:06:29.560 --> 00:06:31.240
And then they can
make the decision

00:06:31.240 --> 00:06:34.870
whether to quit on that
or to at least come up

00:06:34.870 --> 00:06:36.746
with a different method
to try and get there.

