Because again,
that context, that

00:21:39.580 --> 00:21:42.542
shorthand that we develop with
others, that understanding,

00:21:42.542 --> 00:21:43.500
that's really critical.

00:21:43.500 --> 00:21:44.590
And that's when I
talk about the idea

00:21:44.590 --> 00:21:47.320
of knowing yourself but then
also picking the right pond.

00:21:47.320 --> 00:21:50.500
That issue of your
skill set is great.

00:21:50.500 --> 00:21:53.260
But you can be the greatest
guitarist in the world--

00:21:53.260 --> 00:21:56.660
if you work at an
accounting firm,

00:21:56.660 --> 00:21:58.750
that's not very valuable there.

00:21:58.750 --> 00:22:03.080
So it's the skills you have,
and it's where are they?

00:22:03.080 --> 00:22:05.320
Are those valuable
and respected there?

00:22:05.320 --> 00:22:06.940
And it's aligning those two.

00:22:06.940 --> 00:22:09.101
So people have to
think about context.

00:22:09.101 --> 00:22:10.600
The other element
of context is when

00:22:10.600 --> 00:22:12.310
you're talking about
the issue of ethics.

00:22:12.310 --> 00:22:16.210
Where peer pressure influences
all of us not just teenagers.

00:22:16.210 --> 00:22:18.940
So if you're going
to a company--

00:22:18.940 --> 00:22:21.391
Bob Sutton, who's a
professor at Stanford,

00:22:21.391 --> 00:22:23.890
when I talked to him he had a
great quote that I loved where

00:22:23.890 --> 00:22:26.560
he said, whenever you
interview at a company,

00:22:26.560 --> 00:22:28.692
look around at the
people who work there.

00:22:28.692 --> 00:22:30.400
Because you're going
to become like them,

00:22:30.400 --> 00:22:33.440
they're not going
to become like you.

00:22:33.440 --> 00:22:36.430
And if that's not lined up, if
that's not who you want to be,

00:22:36.430 --> 00:22:39.015
then you better really
make another choice.

00:22:39.015 --> 00:22:39.890
SPEAKER 1: It's true.

00:22:39.890 --> 00:22:41.930
Now there's timing
time to context, too.

00:22:41.930 --> 00:22:43.900
If you're a wonder kid--

00:22:43.900 --> 00:22:45.815
could be possibly a
great software engineer,

00:22:45.815 --> 00:22:49.027
but you were born in
the 1940s or '30s.

00:22:49.027 --> 00:22:50.860
ERIC BARKER: I think
Malcolm Gladwell talked

00:22:50.860 --> 00:22:53.830
about that in "Outliers,"
is that issue of timing.

00:22:53.830 --> 00:22:57.200
And also, where is
the organization

00:22:57.200 --> 00:22:59.440
you're looking at working for?

00:22:59.440 --> 00:23:03.060
They might need something
different at a different time.

00:23:03.060 --> 00:23:05.070
If a company is doing
fantastic, again, they

00:23:05.070 --> 00:23:08.670
might need a filtered leader to
just keep it stable and steady.

00:23:08.670 --> 00:23:12.870
If you're in an
industry in decline,

00:23:12.870 --> 00:23:15.780
what they're doing currently
obviously is not working.

00:23:15.780 --> 00:23:17.070
So they need to mix it up.

00:23:17.070 --> 00:23:19.090
They need an unfiltered leader.

00:23:19.090 --> 00:23:22.300
Because if you're headed
towards the ground anyway,

00:23:22.300 --> 00:23:24.510
you might as well take
a change, take a risk,

00:23:24.510 --> 00:23:27.930
and be able to pull out of
it versus just continuing

00:23:27.930 --> 00:23:28.870
what isn't working.

00:23:28.870 --> 00:23:30.626
SPEAKER 1: Gotcha.

00:23:30.626 --> 00:23:32.250
