00:27:12.526 --> 00:27:14.900
SPEAKER 1: So how do we go
about finding the right ponds?

00:27:14.900 --> 00:27:16.454
I think a lot of
introspection, or you

00:27:16.454 --> 00:27:18.120
need to go out there
and get experience.

00:27:18.120 --> 00:27:20.630
What would be the best way?

00:27:20.630 --> 00:27:22.730
ERIC BARKER: The best
thing, first and foremost,

00:27:22.730 --> 00:27:26.810
is to let other people
do the work for you.

00:27:26.810 --> 00:27:29.430
Hey, going out there, we
can each only do so much.

00:27:29.430 --> 00:27:31.520
But you can read online
and then pass that.

00:27:31.520 --> 00:27:33.410
You can talk to people.

00:27:33.410 --> 00:27:34.970
But first, getting
to know yourself,

00:27:34.970 --> 00:27:36.230
getting to know your
signature strengths.

00:27:36.230 --> 00:27:38.036
It's like, what am I
consistently good at?

00:27:38.036 --> 00:27:39.410
And the research
shows a good way

00:27:39.410 --> 00:27:42.440
to go about that is actually
to ask people around you.

00:27:42.440 --> 00:27:46.200
Because when people ask
themselves, what am I good at?

00:27:46.200 --> 00:27:47.780
They're actually
quite bad at it.

00:27:47.780 --> 00:27:49.270
People are not
always good at that.

00:27:49.270 --> 00:27:51.728
But when you ask your friends,
when you ask your coworkers,

00:27:51.728 --> 00:27:54.740
preferably, if you
could do it anonymously,

00:27:54.740 --> 00:27:57.920
if you can have them
kind of submit to it.

00:27:57.920 --> 00:28:00.414
Have a friend filter them
for you so it's anonymous.

00:28:00.414 --> 00:28:02.330
You can get some much
more objective feedback.

00:28:02.330 --> 00:28:03.913
And it turns out
that people around us

00:28:03.913 --> 00:28:07.847
often know our strengths and our
weaknesses better than we do.

00:28:07.847 --> 00:28:09.680
And then something that
Gautam Mukunda talks

00:28:09.680 --> 00:28:13.640
about called intensifiers,
which are qualities that,

00:28:13.640 --> 00:28:17.000
at the mean, are not
necessarily positive,

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:18.890
but in the right context can be.

00:28:18.890 --> 00:28:21.639
So in other words, you might
be somebody who's stubborn.

00:28:21.639 --> 00:28:23.180
Well, in interpersonal
relationships,

00:28:23.180 --> 00:28:24.600
stubbornness is a negative.

00:28:24.600 --> 00:28:27.470
If you're an entrepreneur,
stubbornness is persistence.

00:28:27.470 --> 00:28:29.769
So those qualities are
dependent on context.

00:28:29.769 --> 00:28:31.310
Knowing what your
signature strengths

00:28:31.310 --> 00:28:33.610
are, knowing what your
intensifiers are--

00:28:33.610 --> 00:28:36.740
if you don't have that,
then looking at environments

00:28:36.740 --> 00:28:38.190
isn't going to be very helpful.

00:28:38.190 --> 00:28:39.370
You need to say,
what am I good at?

00:28:39.370 --> 00:28:40.078
What am I bad at?

00:28:40.078 --> 00:28:44.830
And what qualities do I have
that, dependent on context,

00:28:44.830 --> 00:28:46.640
might be positives or negatives?

00:28:46.640 --> 00:28:49.490
And then you can start
to look at what interests

00:28:49.490 --> 00:28:51.770
you, what is aligned
with your skill set.

00:28:51.770 --> 00:28:53.270
You can do a lot
of research online.

00:28:53.270 --> 00:28:55.370
But in the end, you
want to get to a point

00:28:55.370 --> 00:28:56.760
where you're talking to people.

00:28:56.760 --> 00:28:58.404
Because in the end,
it's going to be

00:28:58.404 --> 00:29:00.320
hard to get an honest
answer about the culture

00:29:00.320 --> 00:29:01.160
of an organization.

00:29:01.160 --> 00:29:02.870
Going back to that
Bob Sutton quote on

00:29:02.870 --> 00:29:04.070
"you're going to become
like those people,

00:29:04.070 --> 00:29:05.570
they're not going
to become like you."

00:29:05.570 --> 00:29:07.611
You need to talk to people
who have worked there,

00:29:07.611 --> 00:29:11.510
who are working there to
get an idea of if that's

00:29:11.510 --> 00:29:14.336
going to be a good fit, if
that is the right pond for you.

00:29:14.336 --> 00:29:16.460
SPEAKER 1: What I usually
tell new college grads is

00:29:16.460 --> 00:29:20.510
when you are looking to
learn about a new career is

00:29:20.510 --> 00:29:22.424
to go talk to someone
who is working at NASA.

00:29:22.424 --> 00:29:24.340
What are the three best
things about this job?

00:29:24.340 --> 00:29:25.775
And then what are the three
things that need improvement

00:29:25.775 --> 00:29:26.775
and that you don't like?

00:29:26.775 --> 00:29:29.040
So you can kind of hear
an even keeled take

00:29:29.040 --> 00:29:32.690
on what's going on
in the organization.

00:29:32.690 --> 00:29:34.820
I have Glenn Gould in here.

00:29:34.820 --> 00:29:36.470
So can you tell us
about Glenn Gould?

00:29:36.470 --> 00:29:37.220
ERIC BARKER: Yeah.

00:29:37.220 --> 00:29:41.030
Glenn Gould was considered
one of the greatest

00:29:41.030 --> 00:29:44.420
pianists of the 20th century.

00:29:44.420 --> 00:29:49.100
But he's a very strange
guy, a very, very odd guy.

00:29:49.100 --> 00:29:52.130
And had a lot of crazy quirks.

00:29:52.130 --> 00:29:54.857
He would always wear gloves,
sometimes multiple pairs

00:29:54.857 --> 00:29:55.565
at the same time.

00:29:59.180 --> 00:30:03.350
He had this crazy chair that he
used at every performance that

00:30:03.350 --> 00:30:04.945
was like sloped and low.

00:30:04.945 --> 00:30:06.320
You can actually
hear it creaking

00:30:06.320 --> 00:30:08.310
on the recordings of it.

00:30:08.310 --> 00:30:11.510
But this was a guy who
was so odd and so strange,

00:30:11.510 --> 00:30:15.701
but there's so many environments
he never would have fit in.

00:30:15.701 --> 00:30:16.950
He never would have been fine.

00:30:16.950 --> 00:30:20.960
But finding his thing,
playing the piano,

00:30:20.960 --> 00:30:23.480
and finding the
right environment,

00:30:23.480 --> 00:30:27.080
he's achieved the
highest level that you

00:30:27.080 --> 00:30:29.010
can in terms of celebrity.

00:30:29.010 --> 00:30:31.700
He was mentioned
in "The Simpsons."

00:30:31.700 --> 00:30:32.570
So that's it.

00:30:32.570 --> 00:30:33.800
That's the highest level.

00:30:33.800 --> 00:30:34.880
He's done that.

00:30:34.880 --> 00:30:36.963
He's considered one of the
greatest pianists ever.

00:30:36.963 --> 00:30:38.250
But he's this oddball.

00:30:38.250 --> 00:30:41.540
But he found the right
environment for him.

00:30:41.540 --> 00:30:43.490
And that's what makes
all the difference.

00:30:43.490 --> 00:30:45.031
A lot of people have
a lot of skills.

00:30:45.031 --> 00:30:47.780
But if it's not aligned,
it's not going to work.

00:30:47.780 --> 00:30:49.910
SPEAKER 1: One thing
I see a lot is people

00:30:49.910 --> 00:30:53.387
who are just fantastic
in their line of work,

00:30:53.387 --> 00:30:54.845
but they want to
try something new.

00:30:54.845 --> 00:30:58.360
But they're afraid of getting
started, because it's not

00:30:58.360 --> 00:30:59.570
going to be perfect.

00:30:59.570 --> 00:31:00.470
And I think in
your book you talk

00:31:00.470 --> 00:31:02.420
about it's more about the
quantity of production,

00:31:02.420 --> 00:31:03.920
less about just producing
one great thing.

00:31:03.920 --> 00:31:05.060
Can you talk more about that?

00:31:05.060 --> 00:31:06.601
ERIC BARKER: You
see across the board

00:31:06.601 --> 00:31:10.860
that very often quantity
produces quality.

00:31:10.860 --> 00:31:13.370
The research on
patent applications--

00:31:13.370 --> 00:31:15.350
the people who submit
more patent applications

00:31:15.350 --> 00:31:17.090
end up getting more patents.

00:31:17.090 --> 00:31:20.000
When you look at
scientific research,

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:22.220
the researchers who
produce the most papers

00:31:22.220 --> 00:31:26.000
usually end up with the
handful that are great.

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:29.094
So people who are
more prolific--

00:31:29.094 --> 00:31:31.010
ceteris paribus-- people
who are more prolific

00:31:31.010 --> 00:31:33.050
end up producing
more great stuff.

00:31:33.050 --> 00:31:35.840
So you have to take chances.

00:31:35.840 --> 00:31:38.930
You have to give
things a shot and just

00:31:38.930 --> 00:31:42.680
do more to get out there.

00:31:42.680 --> 00:31:44.420
Sometimes there's
a cost to that.

00:31:44.420 --> 00:31:47.750
But if there isn't, if you
can just put in the hours,

00:31:47.750 --> 00:31:48.350
more work.

00:31:48.350 --> 00:31:50.960
And that, of course, leads to
the work-life balance problem,

00:31:50.960 --> 00:31:55.850
where doing more
does produce results.

00:31:55.850 --> 00:31:58.460
So you have to
know when to stop.

00:31:58.460 --> 00:32:01.610
Because-- ceteris paribus--

00:32:01.610 --> 00:32:04.340
more work, more results.

00:32:04.340 --> 00:32:07.120
You also want to have a
personal life as well.

00:32:07.120 --> 00:32:10.296
SPEAKER 1: How do you find
that balance yourself?

00:32:10.296 --> 00:32:12.170
ERIC BARKER: That's one
that I struggle with.

00:32:12.170 --> 00:32:16.520
But in the end, as I
talk about in the book,

00:32:16.520 --> 00:32:19.021
the issue is, in the
modern era, we talk

00:32:19.021 --> 00:32:20.270
about work-life balance a lot.

00:32:20.270 --> 00:32:21.832
Nobody did 40, 50 years ago.

00:32:21.832 --> 00:32:23.540
And that's because
the world has changed.

00:32:23.540 --> 00:32:27.650
Because now you have your
smartphone in your pocket 24/7.

00:32:27.650 --> 00:32:31.290
You can't say, oh, I left
those papers at the office.

00:32:31.290 --> 00:32:34.070
I'll get them for you
tomorrow at 9:00 AM.

00:32:34.070 --> 00:32:36.050
No, they're available
currently in the cloud.

00:32:36.050 --> 00:32:37.758
You can check your
email wherever you go.

00:32:37.758 --> 00:32:40.040
You always have
the option to work.

00:32:40.040 --> 00:32:43.070
Before, the doors of the
office closed at 5:00 PM.

00:32:43.070 --> 00:32:44.060
Now they don't.

00:32:44.060 --> 00:32:47.690
So basically, the onus
has shifted to us where

00:32:47.690 --> 00:32:49.760
we need to make a decision.

00:32:49.760 --> 00:32:51.500
And that's what's critical.

00:32:51.500 --> 00:32:55.490
So for everyone, the
idea of this go, go, go,

00:32:55.490 --> 00:32:57.770
success as determined
outside yourself

00:32:57.770 --> 00:32:59.780
is going to be
inherently problematic.

00:32:59.780 --> 00:33:01.610
You need a personal
definition of success,

00:33:01.610 --> 00:33:02.990
where you're saying, I'm
going to work this hard.

00:33:02.990 --> 00:33:04.823
And if that means I
don't get the promotion,

00:33:04.823 --> 00:33:05.870
I'm OK with that.

00:33:05.870 --> 00:33:08.480
Or I want that
promotion, and if that

00:33:08.480 --> 00:33:11.420
means I spend less time with
my family, I'm OK with that.

00:33:11.420 --> 00:33:14.330
But the decision has to be
based on a personal definition

00:33:14.330 --> 00:33:14.840
of success.

00:33:14.840 --> 00:33:15.980
What you want.

00:33:15.980 --> 00:33:18.260
Because the world is not
going to decide for you.

00:33:18.260 --> 00:33:20.297
The world is going
to say, keep going,

00:33:20.297 --> 00:33:21.380
keep going until you drop.

00:33:21.380 --> 00:33:22.100
SPEAKER 1: And this
