00:33:23.351 --> 00:33:24.100
ERIC BARKER: Yeah.

00:33:24.100 --> 00:33:26.840
It's choosing the
problems you want to have,

00:33:26.840 --> 00:33:30.645
where it's am I more
comfortable sacrificing

00:33:30.645 --> 00:33:31.760
a bit of my social life?

00:33:31.760 --> 00:33:35.950
Am I more comfortable not
getting that promotion at work?

00:33:35.950 --> 00:33:39.940
But the research that was done--

00:33:39.940 --> 00:33:41.930
I think it was Stevenson
and Nash at Harvard

00:33:41.930 --> 00:33:42.720
did some research.

00:33:42.720 --> 00:33:44.300
And the people who
had gotten closest

00:33:44.300 --> 00:33:47.210
to some approximation
of work-life balance

00:33:47.210 --> 00:33:50.040
had four metrics that
they value their life by.

00:33:50.040 --> 00:33:53.510
And that was happiness,
achievement, significance,

00:33:53.510 --> 00:33:54.500
and legacy.

00:33:54.500 --> 00:33:56.990
Because the problem that
most people do is they

00:33:56.990 --> 00:33:58.730
use a single metric.

00:33:58.730 --> 00:34:01.630
And often that single
metric is money.

00:34:01.630 --> 00:34:03.380
Because it's a number,
and it's made easy.

00:34:03.380 --> 00:34:04.657
Make that go up.

00:34:04.657 --> 00:34:06.740
But then you end up
sacrificing happiness, health,

00:34:06.740 --> 00:34:08.610
relationships, all
these other things.

00:34:08.610 --> 00:34:11.510
So you need this
balance of the four.

00:34:11.510 --> 00:34:13.330
Happiness-- do you
enjoy what you're doing?

00:34:13.330 --> 00:34:15.413
Achievement-- are you
getting ahead in your goals?

00:34:15.413 --> 00:34:19.100
Significance-- is what you're
doing positively affecting

00:34:19.100 --> 00:34:20.717
those around you that you love?

00:34:20.717 --> 00:34:23.300
And legacy-- to some degree, are
you making the world a better

00:34:23.300 --> 00:34:23.980
place?

00:34:23.980 --> 00:34:26.449
And people who, if you look
at your schedule and you say,

00:34:26.449 --> 00:34:29.210
