00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:25.851
studies is writing
down three good things

00:43:25.851 --> 00:43:28.350
that happened to you that day
before you go to bed at night.

00:43:28.350 --> 00:43:29.310
Why?

00:43:29.310 --> 00:43:32.700
Because it makes them
more top of mind.

00:43:32.700 --> 00:43:34.560
Tons of good things
happen to you every day.

00:43:34.560 --> 00:43:36.910
Tons of bad things
happen to you every day.

00:43:36.910 --> 00:43:38.880
So you can only
focus on so much.

00:43:38.880 --> 00:43:40.914
You only have so much
bandwidth in your head.

00:43:40.914 --> 00:43:42.330
So what's going
to be top of mind?

00:43:42.330 --> 00:43:44.190
What are you going
to remember that day?

00:43:44.190 --> 00:43:45.670
What are you going to
remember from that day?

00:43:45.670 --> 00:43:47.700
And if you take the time
with those three things,

00:43:47.700 --> 00:43:48.825
you're going to be happier.

00:43:48.825 --> 00:43:53.754
So gratitude, Shawn Achor,
one thing he recommends,

00:43:53.754 --> 00:43:55.170
is the first thing
you do when you

00:43:55.170 --> 00:43:56.628
get in the office
every day is just

00:43:56.628 --> 00:43:58.140
sit down and write
a thank you email

00:43:58.140 --> 00:44:00.250
or send a thank you
text to someone else.

00:44:00.250 --> 00:44:01.350
It'll make them feel good.

00:44:01.350 --> 00:44:02.550
It'll make you feel good.

00:44:02.550 --> 00:44:04.730
And how you feel in the
morning, the research shows,

00:44:04.730 --> 00:44:06.470
affects the rest of your day.

00:44:06.470 --> 00:44:08.880
It's a very simple
happiness exercise

00:44:08.880 --> 00:44:11.610
and critical for
connecting with people.

00:44:11.610 --> 00:44:13.840
Showing them that they
are valuable to you.

00:44:13.840 --> 00:44:16.090
SPEAKER 1: I have a calendar
reminder for every Friday

00:44:16.090 --> 00:44:17.470
to send out a thank
you to somebody.

00:44:17.470 --> 00:44:18.115
ERIC BARKER: Absolutely.

00:44:18.115 --> 00:44:19.906
SPEAKER 1: And another
point you brought up

00:44:19.906 --> 00:44:21.079
is doing your homework.

00:44:21.079 --> 00:44:22.620
After someone gives
you an assignment

00:44:22.620 --> 00:44:24.510
for connecting with
them, actually coming

00:44:24.510 --> 00:44:26.290
back full circle
and saying, hey, you

00:44:26.290 --> 00:44:27.330
told me to do this and whatnot.

00:44:27.330 --> 00:44:28.413
ERIC BARKER: Following up.

00:44:28.413 --> 00:44:29.790
That's critical with mentors.

00:44:29.790 --> 00:44:32.474
Because there's nothing that's
going to irritate mentors

00:44:32.474 --> 00:44:34.140
more than when they
give you good advice

00:44:34.140 --> 00:44:36.090
and you don't actually
follow through with it.

00:44:36.090 --> 00:44:39.720
So listening to
what a mentor says,

00:44:39.720 --> 00:44:42.540
it also allows you to stay
in touch with the mentor.

00:44:42.540 --> 00:44:44.634
Because if the mentor is
actually really valuable,

00:44:44.634 --> 00:44:46.050
they're probably
going to be busy.

00:44:46.050 --> 00:44:47.670
You hope they're
going to be busy.

00:44:47.670 --> 00:44:49.170
They've got a lot
of stuff going on.

00:44:49.170 --> 00:44:51.377
So they give you advice,
you go, you follow through

00:44:51.377 --> 00:44:51.960
on the advice.

00:44:51.960 --> 00:44:53.550
You get the result,
you come back.

00:44:53.550 --> 00:44:55.883
Now you can say, hey, I
followed through on your advice,

00:44:55.883 --> 00:44:56.850
here are the results.

00:44:56.850 --> 00:44:58.660
I'm thinking about
what I should do next.

00:44:58.660 --> 00:45:00.220
I've put some thought into it.

00:45:00.220 --> 00:45:01.262
Here's two possibilities.

00:45:01.262 --> 00:45:02.844
If you have a chance,
I'd love to hear

00:45:02.844 --> 00:45:05.280
what you think would be a
best and next step for me.

00:45:05.280 --> 00:45:07.260
That's a great way to
keep a relationship

00:45:07.260 --> 00:45:09.210
with a mentor going.

00:45:09.210 --> 00:45:12.655
And it's flattering to them that
somebody is taking their advice

00:45:12.655 --> 00:45:14.280
and actually following
through with it.

00:45:14.280 --> 00:45:15.180
It sounds simple.

00:45:15.180 --> 00:45:16.260
It sounds stupid.

00:45:16.260 --> 00:45:19.810
But the truth is so
many people just don't.

00:45:19.810 --> 00:45:22.890
They'll bother a busy
person, ask him a question,

00:45:22.890 --> 00:45:23.940
and then not do it.

00:45:23.940 --> 00:45:26.760
If you did and you document
it, you got positive results.

00:45:26.760 --> 00:45:29.670
And then you're asking their
advice, that's the thing.

00:45:29.670 --> 00:45:32.370
And if you're somebody
who does their homework--

00:45:32.370 --> 00:45:35.820
So many people, so many
busy, successful people,

00:45:35.820 --> 00:45:37.950
it's like they get people
clamoring for their time,

00:45:37.950 --> 00:45:39.199
but they don't follow through.

00:45:39.199 --> 00:45:40.851
Those people didn't
do their homework.

00:45:40.851 --> 00:45:42.600
You don't need to ask
the head-- if you're

00:45:42.600 --> 00:45:43.620
looking for
investment advice, you

00:45:43.620 --> 00:45:45.960
don't need to contact
the CEO of Goldman Sachs.

00:45:45.960 --> 00:45:47.550
There's easier ways to do it.

00:45:47.550 --> 00:45:49.070
So you want to make sure you're
asking the right questions.

00:45:49.070 --> 00:45:50.111
Did you do your homework?

00:45:50.111 --> 00:45:52.800
Is this the person you have
to talk to to get the answer?

00:45:52.800 --> 00:45:56.750
If you've done that much work,
you're going to impress people.

00:45:56.750 --> 00:46:00.450
You're going to stand out
above the other 99.9% of people

00:46:00.450 --> 00:46:01.800
who reach out to them.

00:46:01.800 --> 00:46:03.606
So following through,
doing your homework,

00:46:03.606 --> 00:46:04.980
it really makes
a difference when

00:46:04.980 --> 00:46:06.440
you're trying to
make relationships

00:46:06.440 --> 00:46:08.305
with potential mentors.

00:46:08.305 --> 00:46:09.930
SPEAKER 1: And then,
also, these people

00:46:09.930 --> 00:46:12.450
have busy family lives
with their careers.

00:46:12.450 --> 00:46:15.340
If someone comes up
to you and says, hey,

00:46:15.340 --> 00:46:17.230
can you be my mentor?

00:46:17.230 --> 00:46:19.740
Well, I'm thinking of a
terribly long time commitment

00:46:19.740 --> 00:46:21.300
that person does not have.

00:46:21.300 --> 00:46:23.130
So I always looked
at it as friendships.

00:46:23.130 --> 00:46:26.265
It's like maybe I can
research as much as

00:46:26.265 --> 00:46:27.890
possible of this
person on the internet

00:46:27.890 --> 00:46:28.889
without being a stalker.

00:46:28.889 --> 00:46:30.630
But going on their
blog, learning.

00:46:30.630 --> 00:46:32.310
And then if I have a question
that can't be answered,

00:46:32.310 --> 00:46:34.020
make sure it's something that
can be answered within five

00:46:34.020 --> 00:46:36.850
minutes and doesn't require them
to write their life story out.

00:46:36.850 --> 00:46:37.060
ERIC BARKER: No.

00:46:37.060 --> 00:46:38.518
And what you see
in the research is

00:46:38.518 --> 00:46:40.140
that the best
mentor relationships

00:46:40.140 --> 00:46:41.580
become like friendships.

00:46:41.580 --> 00:46:43.995
But asking that, will
you be my mentor?

00:46:43.995 --> 00:46:45.370
It's kind of like
asking somebody

00:46:45.370 --> 00:46:47.940
to marry you on the first date.

00:46:47.940 --> 00:46:49.830
That's a huge
commitment to somebody

00:46:49.830 --> 00:46:51.900
who just emailed me and
asked me a question.

00:46:51.900 --> 00:46:55.020
And they had like six
spelling errors in the email.

00:46:55.020 --> 00:46:59.252
Versus asking questions,
showing you did the work,

00:46:59.252 --> 00:47:00.960
showing that you're
somebody who's smart,

00:47:00.960 --> 00:47:03.600
and showing them that
they are the right person

00:47:03.600 --> 00:47:04.890
to ask that question to.

00:47:04.890 --> 00:47:07.560
But there is no other way.

00:47:07.560 --> 00:47:09.090
I want to be this level of Jedi.

00:47:09.090 --> 00:47:11.450
I got to talk to Yoda.

00:47:11.450 --> 00:47:12.990
They're the perfect
person for this.

00:47:12.990 --> 00:47:13.790
That's respectful.

00:47:13.790 --> 00:47:15.440
You're respecting their time.

00:47:15.440 --> 00:47:17.384
You are not putting
all the effort on them.

00:47:17.384 --> 00:47:19.800
This is not something that can
be answered with one Google

00:47:19.800 --> 00:47:20.550
search.

00:47:20.550 --> 00:47:24.000
It's like this is something
that shows them that you

00:47:24.000 --> 00:47:25.856
are an A player like they are.

00:47:25.856 --> 00:47:27.480
You're trying to get
to the next level,

00:47:27.480 --> 00:47:29.188
and they are the right
person to talk to.

00:47:29.188 --> 00:47:30.940
And that's how you
get a good mentor.

00:47:30.940 --> 00:47:31.420
SPEAKER 1: That's true.

00:47:31.420 --> 00:47:32.836
And then, also,
the introductions,

00:47:32.836 --> 00:47:34.530
the double opt-in introduction.

00:47:34.530 --> 00:47:36.399
First, I would go to Eric.

00:47:36.399 --> 00:47:38.440
Because, let's say, I want
Eric to talk to Brian.

00:47:38.440 --> 00:47:39.690
And then Brian's good for Eric.

00:47:39.690 --> 00:47:41.920
First, I'll go to Eric, ask if
he's OK with the introduction.

00:47:41.920 --> 00:47:43.760
Then I'll go back to
Brian, explain to him

00:47:43.760 --> 00:47:45.310
why it's beneficial
to meet Eric.

00:47:45.310 --> 00:47:46.920
And if he agrees, I'll
introduce them both.

00:47:46.920 --> 00:47:48.878
Because I'm sure you get
a lot of introductions

00:47:48.878 --> 00:47:50.400
where it's like--

00:47:50.400 --> 00:47:52.469
ERIC BARKER: Hey, here's
somebody you really

00:47:52.469 --> 00:47:53.760
have no interest in talking to.

00:47:53.760 --> 00:47:55.057
Why don't you guys chat?

00:47:55.057 --> 00:47:55.971
No.

00:47:55.971 --> 00:47:56.820
How about we don't.

00:47:59.910 --> 00:48:02.760
SPEAKER 1: So for my last online
question, this is from Lisa.

00:48:02.760 --> 00:48:05.197
She says, there's a lot of
information in your book

00:48:05.197 --> 00:48:07.030
and a lot of information
to learn and retain

00:48:07.030 --> 00:48:08.180
to day-to-day life.

00:48:08.180 --> 00:48:13.070
In your opinion, how should
we retain all this information

00:48:13.070 --> 00:48:16.400
and how much of it?

00:48:16.400 --> 00:48:19.520
ERIC BARKER: I don't
think that everybody needs

00:48:19.520 --> 00:48:22.010
to learn everything in there.

00:48:22.010 --> 00:48:24.500
I think there's areas
we're they're strong.

00:48:24.500 --> 00:48:26.295
There's areas
where they're weak.

00:48:26.295 --> 00:48:28.730
Some people might be
in a great situation

00:48:28.730 --> 00:48:32.660
in terms of the nice
guys finish last issue.

00:48:32.660 --> 00:48:34.360
They might be
surrounded by other--

00:48:34.360 --> 00:48:35.735
in Adam Grant's
terminology, they

00:48:35.735 --> 00:48:37.360
might be surrounded
about other givers.

00:48:37.360 --> 00:48:38.450
Might be a good place.

00:48:38.450 --> 00:48:39.770
That might not be something
they're worried about.

00:48:39.770 --> 00:48:40.700
But they might
have a big problem

00:48:40.700 --> 00:48:42.080
with the work-life
balance issue.

00:48:42.080 --> 00:48:46.250
Or somebody might be
really great at networking,

00:48:46.250 --> 00:48:48.350
but they might have a
real confidence issue.

00:48:48.350 --> 00:48:51.830
Focus on the stuff that is going
to benefit them individually.

00:48:51.830 --> 00:48:53.030
Like what goals do you have?

00:48:53.030 --> 00:48:54.710
What serves those goals?

00:48:54.710 --> 00:48:57.290
Don't try and do everything.

00:48:57.290 --> 00:49:00.380
Pick one thing, get that
right, and then move on

00:49:00.380 --> 00:49:02.360
to what is of
secondary interest.

00:49:02.360 --> 00:49:06.290
So there's no need
to exhaustively go

00:49:06.290 --> 00:49:08.510
through every piece
of advice in there.

00:49:08.510 --> 00:49:09.510
SPEAKER 1: Excellent.

00:49:09.510 --> 00:49:13.670
Do we have you
in-audience questions?

00:49:13.670 --> 00:49:17.090
We're going to get
you a mic real quick.

00:49:17.090 --> 00:49:20.700
AUDIENCE: I also wrote a book
on the science of success.

00:49:20.700 --> 00:49:26.210
And I was completely
shocked, because I

00:49:26.210 --> 00:49:28.610
