And he'd beat up on him so.

00:51:09.350 --> 00:51:11.810
So it was completely the
opposite of everything

00:51:11.810 --> 00:51:15.360
I ever heard in all of
the literature out there.

00:51:15.360 --> 00:51:18.510
But these were the number
one people in their field.

00:51:18.510 --> 00:51:20.480
Any comments?

00:51:20.480 --> 00:51:22.702
ERIC BARKER: There are
exceptions to every rule.

00:51:22.702 --> 00:51:24.160
There are exceptions
to every rule.

00:51:24.160 --> 00:51:26.750
AUDIENCE: Here's
another question.

00:51:26.750 --> 00:51:29.930
How many of the success
books out there actually are

00:51:29.930 --> 00:51:33.380
able to get the number
one person in the world

00:51:33.380 --> 00:51:36.950
and follow them around with
cameras, and videotape, et

00:51:36.950 --> 00:51:39.420
cetera?

00:51:39.420 --> 00:51:44.090
Scientific studies, if you
look at them, other than Xerox

00:51:44.090 --> 00:51:46.190
professional selling
skills, which

00:51:46.190 --> 00:51:50.360
studied slightly above average
people, but not the very best.

00:51:50.360 --> 00:51:52.812
None of them, at least
in the field of sales,

00:51:52.812 --> 00:51:55.370
had actually gone out and
followed around number one

00:51:55.370 --> 00:51:56.100
people.

00:51:56.100 --> 00:51:57.820
None of them because
they can't get them.

00:51:57.820 --> 00:51:59.900
They're impossible.

00:51:59.900 --> 00:52:05.380
So I think a lot of what is
reported in success literature

00:52:05.380 --> 00:52:08.650
is the average people or
the slightly above average.

00:52:08.650 --> 00:52:13.240
And it's a lot of researchers
quoting each other and others'

00:52:13.240 --> 00:52:13.960
research.

00:52:13.960 --> 00:52:19.200
And quoting and doing
research of groups

00:52:19.200 --> 00:52:25.220
that are below average,
or medium, or mediocre,

00:52:25.220 --> 00:52:26.830
but not the very best.

00:52:26.830 --> 00:52:29.950
How many actually go out and
study number one in the world?

00:52:31.900 --> 00:52:33.650
ERIC BARKER: There are
a number of studies

00:52:33.650 --> 00:52:36.020
that looked at some of the
top people in the world.

00:52:36.020 --> 00:52:39.880
But it depends
specifically on what's

00:52:39.880 --> 00:52:43.130
your question in terms of
their attitude, in terms of--

00:52:43.130 --> 00:52:44.620
again, there's success.

00:52:44.620 --> 00:52:46.240
There's also happiness.

00:52:46.240 --> 00:52:47.650
Those can be very different.

00:52:47.650 --> 00:52:51.730
And attitudes do vary
based on profession.

00:52:51.730 --> 00:52:57.460
So being optimistic produces
persistence, produces grit.

00:52:57.460 --> 00:53:00.220
That doesn't necessarily
mean-- again,

00:53:00.220 --> 00:53:02.530
if it's in an industry
that is doomed,

00:53:02.530 --> 00:53:06.230
persistence is not going
to result in success.

00:53:06.230 --> 00:53:09.430
So I think it has to be
very specific on what

00:53:09.430 --> 00:53:10.730
you are studying.

00:53:10.730 --> 00:53:14.110
If you look at attorneys,
attorneys usually

00:53:14.110 --> 00:53:18.040
score far higher on
pessimism and negativity

00:53:18.040 --> 00:53:19.390
than most other people.

00:53:19.390 --> 00:53:23.110
It is because it is a
beneficial quality in law.

00:53:23.110 --> 00:53:25.630
Because you need, when
you're doing a contract,

00:53:25.630 --> 00:53:28.750
to consider everything that
could go wrong and make sure

00:53:28.750 --> 00:53:30.550
your client is covered for that.

00:53:30.550 --> 00:53:32.980
So pessimism is a benefit.

00:53:32.980 --> 00:53:35.260
And if you score
higher in pessimism,

00:53:35.260 --> 00:53:38.210
you score higher on the
LSAT across the board.

00:53:38.210 --> 00:53:42.220
So entrepreneurs,
as well, negativity

00:53:42.220 --> 00:53:43.512
can be a benefit in the sense--

00:53:43.512 --> 00:53:45.344
AUDIENCE: Otherwise you
don't push yourself.

00:53:45.344 --> 00:53:46.380
ERIC BARKER: Yeah.

00:53:46.380 --> 00:53:49.930
So the qualities vary in
terms of what the role is.

00:53:49.930 --> 00:53:52.819
But also, you also have be
very specific about what

00:53:52.819 --> 00:53:53.610
you're looking for.

00:53:53.610 --> 00:53:54.730
Are you talking
about persistence?

00:53:54.730 --> 00:53:56.810
Or are you talking
about financial success?

00:53:56.810 --> 00:53:58.840
Or are you talking about
personal happiness?

00:53:58.840 --> 00:54:00.850
So what you're looking at--

00:54:00.850 --> 00:54:02.300
those can vary dramatically.

00:54:02.300 --> 00:54:04.960
So it depends on how
specific the study is

00:54:04.960 --> 00:54:07.950
and what they're measuring.

00:54:07.950 --> 00:54:10.990
SPEAKER 1: Do we have
any other questions?

00:54:10.990 --> 00:54:13.440
Alice, I think we have one
more and then we'll wrap up.

00:54:17.984 --> 00:54:19.650
AUDIENCE: Thank you
for your talk today.

00:54:19.650 --> 00:54:22.860
So a quick question I have
is, when people usually

00:54:22.860 --> 00:54:25.854
talk about connecting
people or networking--

00:54:25.854 --> 00:54:27.270
actually, you
should know the idea

00:54:27.270 --> 00:54:29.400
that comes to my
mind is why don't we

00:54:29.400 --> 00:54:34.470
just do self-improvement
other than networking?

00:54:34.470 --> 00:54:37.554
Maybe for myself, I seldom
go to networking events.

00:54:37.554 --> 00:54:38.970
Actually, I never
think about just

00:54:38.970 --> 00:54:40.500
trying to connect with people.

00:54:40.500 --> 00:54:42.450
I'm thinking about when
I was back in school

00:54:42.450 --> 00:54:43.560
I really loved what I was doing.

00:54:43.560 --> 00:54:44.790
I was a mechanical engineer.

00:54:44.790 --> 00:54:48.190
I just enjoy when I was
dealing with mechanical stuff.

00:54:48.190 --> 00:54:49.980
And then I think
that's actually maybe

00:54:49.980 --> 00:54:51.592
why I actually get
you more and more

00:54:51.592 --> 00:54:52.800
familiar with what I'm doing.

00:54:52.800 --> 00:54:54.508
And maybe sometimes
showing better skills

00:54:54.508 --> 00:54:56.370
than the peer
students around me.

00:54:56.370 --> 00:54:59.442
And actually why I'm
hired here at Google.

00:54:59.442 --> 00:55:00.150
Maybe that's why.

00:55:00.150 --> 00:55:03.450
But compared with
my peer friends,

00:55:03.450 --> 00:55:06.034
maybe they're always
trying to get connected

00:55:06.034 --> 00:55:06.950
with people in Google.

00:55:06.950 --> 00:55:08.408
But actually they
cannot come here.

00:55:08.408 --> 00:55:10.540
But for me, I'm just
focusing on myself,

00:55:10.540 --> 00:55:12.900
focusing on what I
think I should be doing.

00:55:12.900 --> 00:55:14.380
But actually I come here.

00:55:14.380 --> 00:55:17.110
And I know a lot
of Google people

00:55:17.110 --> 00:55:19.300
without thinking about
networking with people.

00:55:19.300 --> 00:55:22.380
So how would you
think about that when

00:55:22.380 --> 00:55:26.390
we're comparing self-improvement
and connecting networking,

00:55:26.390 --> 00:55:27.940
I would say?

00:55:27.940 --> 00:55:29.550
ERIC BARKER: In
the book I do talk

00:55:29.550 --> 00:55:31.530
about those two distinctions.

00:55:31.530 --> 00:55:37.480
Where what you see is that
extroverts score much higher

00:55:37.480 --> 00:55:40.350
in a number of success
metrics because

00:55:40.350 --> 00:55:41.910
of networking abilities.

00:55:41.910 --> 00:55:45.360
On the flip side,
introverts very often

00:55:45.360 --> 00:55:47.520
excel in terms of
individual performance.

00:55:47.520 --> 00:55:50.940
In fact, there's one
study, the jargon

00:55:50.940 --> 00:55:54.450
was something like extroversion
is inversely correlated

00:55:54.450 --> 00:55:56.007
with individual performance.

00:55:56.007 --> 00:55:57.840
Or basically, the more
extroverted you were,

00:55:57.840 --> 00:55:59.506
the worse you were at your job.

00:55:59.506 --> 00:56:02.130
If you're spending a lot of time
hanging out with your friends,

00:56:02.130 --> 00:56:05.940
you're probably not spending
those 10,000 hours of practice.

00:56:05.940 --> 00:56:08.580
So both are very valuable.

00:56:08.580 --> 00:56:12.720
But on average, having that
network, just because you

00:56:12.720 --> 00:56:16.170
have those skills, making sure
that the right people know

00:56:16.170 --> 00:56:19.590
you have those skills can
make a huge difference.

00:56:19.590 --> 00:56:21.870
How does that resume get
in front of the person

00:56:21.870 --> 00:56:24.570
when there's 1,000
other resumes?

00:56:24.570 --> 00:56:28.140
Or when you're talking about
a much more informal system,

00:56:28.140 --> 00:56:32.220
like Hollywood, where there's
not an HR department to become

00:56:32.220 --> 00:56:33.510
a director of a movie.

00:56:33.510 --> 00:56:36.810
It's all made based on
individual discretion.

00:56:36.810 --> 00:56:40.530
Networking is essential, because
there is no formal system

00:56:40.530 --> 00:56:43.650
by which to submit your resume.

00:56:43.650 --> 00:56:47.800
So that level of visibility
makes a big difference.

00:56:47.800 --> 00:56:50.910
And let's face
it, how often when

00:56:50.910 --> 00:56:54.922
you buy something, if you
aren't sure which laptop to get,

00:56:54.922 --> 00:56:56.630
you're probably going
to ask your friend.

00:56:56.630 --> 00:56:58.380
Your friend's going
to say, get this one.

00:56:58.380 --> 00:56:59.830
And you might go with it.

00:56:59.830 --> 00:57:01.970
Same thing happens
with hiring decisions.

00:57:01.970 --> 00:57:03.360
Big stack of resumes.

00:57:03.360 --> 00:57:05.735
All are pretty good.

00:57:05.735 --> 00:57:06.610
Who do you recommend?

00:57:06.610 --> 00:57:08.970
Well, I know that one guy
who-- and you're probably

00:57:08.970 --> 00:57:10.050
going to go with them.

00:57:10.050 --> 00:57:11.910
And that happens all the time.

00:57:11.910 --> 00:57:14.010
So it's a balance
between the two.

00:57:14.010 --> 00:57:17.460
If you are more introverted, you
don't enjoy networking as much.

00:57:17.460 --> 00:57:19.119
It's like focus on
building skills.

00:57:19.119 --> 00:57:20.910
But that doesn't mean
that networking still

00:57:20.910 --> 00:57:21.870
doesn't have its value.

00:57:21.870 --> 00:57:24.570
And on the other hand,
hey, networks are great.

00:57:24.570 --> 00:57:27.194
But if you're not
good at your job,

00:57:27.194 --> 00:57:28.860
that's going to be
found out eventually,

00:57:28.860 --> 00:57:30.600
and you may not have
that job very long.

00:57:30.600 --> 00:57:32.820
So there is a
balance of the two.

00:57:32.820 --> 00:57:37.800
I don't think you can really
get to the highest levels

00:57:37.800 --> 00:57:40.440
without either an
enormous amount of luck

00:57:40.440 --> 00:57:42.776
or a balance between both.

